1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,440
You know, if I asked you right now to tell me the exact difference between a wink and a blink,

2
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:08,640
you would probably think I was setting up some terrible dad joke.

3
00:00:08,880 --> 00:00:11,160
Right, yeah, like there's a punchline coming.

4
00:00:11,480 --> 00:00:11,880
Exactly.

5
00:00:12,280 --> 00:00:17,420
You'd probably say something along the lines of, well, I mean, I wink, but a blink just sort of,

6
00:00:17,580 --> 00:00:19,080
it just happens on its own.

7
00:00:19,540 --> 00:00:26,980
Like one is this deliberate choice you make on purpose to, you know, signal a friend across a

8
00:00:26,980 --> 00:00:34,000
crowded room, and the other is just a reflex, just an automatic biological function to keep

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:35,480
your eyeball from drying out.

10
00:00:35,700 --> 00:00:39,440
Yeah, it seems like the most obvious, simple distinction in the world, right?

11
00:00:39,480 --> 00:00:39,840
Totally.

12
00:00:40,200 --> 00:00:43,920
But the wild thing is, and this really blew my mind when we started looking into this,

13
00:00:44,880 --> 00:00:50,900
determining the exact rigorous boundary between a wink and a blink, like between an action and a

14
00:00:50,900 --> 00:00:56,780
mere physical event, it's actually one of the most notoriously difficult unsolved problems

15
00:00:56,780 --> 00:01:00,420
in the entire history of science and philosophy.

16
00:01:00,780 --> 00:01:01,460
Oh, absolutely.

17
00:01:01,820 --> 00:01:07,480
And I mean, it sounds absurd until you realize the actual stakes involved.

18
00:01:07,480 --> 00:01:14,880
This isn't just some academic puzzle for people in tweed jackets arguing in like university lounges.

19
00:01:15,340 --> 00:01:16,300
Think about a courtroom.

20
00:01:16,820 --> 00:01:21,920
When jurors are sitting in a murder trial, they don't just look at a deceased victim and say,

21
00:01:22,540 --> 00:01:26,560
well, the body has ceased biological function, case closed.

22
00:01:26,780 --> 00:01:27,140
Right.

23
00:01:27,300 --> 00:01:28,260
That would be insane.

24
00:01:28,380 --> 00:01:28,820
Exactly.

25
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:34,800
They are specifically tasked with figuring out the intent behind the physical event.

26
00:01:35,200 --> 00:01:38,320
Was it a premeditated first degree murder?

27
00:01:38,660 --> 00:01:39,760
Was it an accident?

28
00:01:39,960 --> 00:01:40,900
You know, manslaughter?

29
00:01:41,460 --> 00:01:45,820
Did the defendant pull the trigger on purpose, executing this planned action?

30
00:01:46,100 --> 00:01:51,760
Or did a loud noise startle them and cause an involuntary muscle spasm in their finger?

31
00:01:52,220 --> 00:01:52,580
Wow.

32
00:01:52,580 --> 00:01:55,260
Yeah, when you frame it like that, it's huge.

33
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:55,840
It is.

34
00:01:55,900 --> 00:02:02,100
Our entire legal system, our whole framework for moral judgments, guilt, innocence,

35
00:02:02,100 --> 00:02:10,540
all of it rests completely on this incredibly shadowy, undefined border between voluntary action and involuntary behavior.

36
00:02:10,900 --> 00:02:13,300
So that is our mission for this deep dive.

37
00:02:13,300 --> 00:02:20,940
We are going to completely deconstruct how human beings actually act, how we emote, and how we make decisions.

38
00:02:21,060 --> 00:02:21,240
Yeah.

39
00:02:21,360 --> 00:02:25,600
And to do that, we really have to throw out centuries of completely outdated science.

40
00:02:25,820 --> 00:02:26,380
We do.

41
00:02:26,640 --> 00:02:26,860
Yeah.

42
00:02:27,020 --> 00:02:30,460
We are pulling from two intensely fascinating sources today.

43
00:02:30,460 --> 00:02:42,800
The first is Alicia Guerrero's Dynamics in Action, which just completely dismantles how philosophers and scientists have thought about cause and effect in human behavior.

44
00:02:42,980 --> 00:02:45,160
It really tears the whole foundation down.

45
00:02:45,160 --> 00:03:03,980
And the second is this cutting-edge paper, From Catharsis to Geometric Bayesianism, RSVP and Demise of the Hydraulic Model of Emotion, which, and this is crazy, uses physics and math to prove why venting your anger is actually making you worse.

46
00:03:03,980 --> 00:03:15,100
Yes. The overarching theme we really have to confront here is that for hundreds of years, humanity has relied on these mechanical metaphors to understand the mind.

47
00:03:15,500 --> 00:03:15,680
Right.

48
00:03:15,960 --> 00:03:25,600
We've treated the brain like a complex clockwork mechanism with gears and springs, or later on, like a pressure cooker holding back volatile fluids.

49
00:03:25,680 --> 00:03:26,740
The old Freudian thing.

50
00:03:26,820 --> 00:03:27,260
Exactly.

51
00:03:27,260 --> 00:03:38,920
But what the most recent breakthroughs in physics and biology are showing us is that treating the human brain and behavior like a highly sensitive, constantly shifting weather system is vastly more accurate.

52
00:03:39,460 --> 00:03:43,640
A weather system. I love that. I really want to hold on to that image.

53
00:03:43,900 --> 00:03:44,080
Yeah.

54
00:03:44,180 --> 00:03:47,480
But before we get to the weather, we have to start with the clockwork.

55
00:03:47,620 --> 00:03:48,680
Yeah, we have to go back.

56
00:03:49,040 --> 00:03:53,960
Way back. We need to figure out how we got it so catastrophically wrong in the first place.

57
00:03:53,960 --> 00:03:58,940
And that takes us back, like, 2,500 years to ancient Greece.

58
00:03:59,920 --> 00:04:01,780
It all begins with Aristotle.

59
00:04:02,260 --> 00:04:03,720
Good old Aristotle.

60
00:04:04,060 --> 00:04:10,980
Right. He established this fundamental rule of physics that has essentially haunted philosophy and science ever since.

61
00:04:11,220 --> 00:04:14,740
He stated that nothing can move or cause itself.

62
00:04:15,060 --> 00:04:18,540
And, I mean, you really have to put yourself in Aristotle's shoes for a second.

63
00:04:18,540 --> 00:04:23,580
He was trying to build a coherent framework for how change happens in the universe.

64
00:04:23,960 --> 00:04:25,780
Right. He's just looking around at rocks and stuff.

65
00:04:25,880 --> 00:04:33,800
Exactly. He was observing the natural world, the mechanics of everyday life, and he established what seemed like an airtight principle.

66
00:04:34,440 --> 00:04:38,660
If a stone is rolling down a hill, something had to have pushed it.

67
00:04:38,760 --> 00:04:39,360
Makes sense.

68
00:04:39,660 --> 00:04:39,940
Right.

69
00:04:39,940 --> 00:04:44,660
A physical object cannot spontaneously act upon itself.

70
00:04:45,860 --> 00:04:49,920
One part of a system has to impart force onto another part.

71
00:04:50,240 --> 00:04:54,280
It sounds completely logical, almost undeniable.

72
00:04:54,720 --> 00:04:56,840
Until you look at anything that's actually alive.

73
00:04:56,960 --> 00:04:57,280
Tingo.

74
00:04:57,280 --> 00:05:09,920
It creates this monumental, system-breaking headache the absolute second you try to apply that rule to living, breathing organisms.

75
00:05:10,320 --> 00:05:13,720
Because organisms clearly constantly move themselves.

76
00:05:14,120 --> 00:05:22,400
There is this wild medical story from the 1950s that illustrates this exact philosophical terror perfectly.

77
00:05:22,580 --> 00:05:24,180
Oh, I know the one you're talking about.

78
00:05:24,180 --> 00:05:25,200
It's so creepy.

79
00:05:25,980 --> 00:05:29,480
There was this pioneering neurosurgeon named Wilder Penfield.

80
00:05:30,020 --> 00:05:34,640
He was performing surgeries on awake patients who suffered from severe epilepsy.

81
00:05:35,060 --> 00:05:37,760
Awake brain surgery is always a wild concept.

82
00:05:37,980 --> 00:05:38,200
Yeah.

83
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:39,000
Terrifying.

84
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:49,960
So to find the source of the seizures, he would open their skulls, expose their brains, and use this tiny electrical probe to literally poke specific areas of the cortex.

85
00:05:50,180 --> 00:05:50,600
Right.

86
00:05:50,840 --> 00:05:58,700
He would stimulate the motor cortex, and suddenly the patient would raise their arm, or their hand would clench, or they would just blurt out a random vowel sound.

87
00:05:59,340 --> 00:06:03,240
But the profound part is what the patient said when he did this.

88
00:06:03,240 --> 00:06:05,700
They never claimed ownership of the movement.

89
00:06:06,100 --> 00:06:06,460
Never.

90
00:06:06,940 --> 00:06:08,480
They would immediately protest.

91
00:06:08,700 --> 00:06:12,600
They'd look at the surgeon in an absolute panic and say, I didn't do that.

92
00:06:12,700 --> 00:06:14,040
You pulled that out of me.

93
00:06:14,420 --> 00:06:17,120
Or they'd say, my arm moved, but I didn't move it.

94
00:06:17,160 --> 00:06:18,520
Which is deeply unsettling.

95
00:06:18,640 --> 00:06:18,980
Totally.

96
00:06:19,420 --> 00:06:20,620
Their muscles contracted.

97
00:06:20,860 --> 00:06:22,380
Their vocal cords vibrated.

98
00:06:22,380 --> 00:06:28,860
The biological mechanism worked flawlessly, but they felt absolutely zero internal agency.

99
00:06:29,900 --> 00:06:32,420
From the outside, it looked like an action.

100
00:06:32,800 --> 00:06:35,640
From the inside, it was just an event happening to them.

101
00:06:35,680 --> 00:06:37,200
It was a blink, not a wink.

102
00:06:37,200 --> 00:06:42,140
Which perfectly encapsulates Aristotle's dilemma regarding the origin of movement.

103
00:06:43,060 --> 00:06:50,300
If Wilder Penfield's electrical probe is what causes the arm to rise, the origin of the movement is clearly external.

104
00:06:50,300 --> 00:06:53,120
It is an alien force acting upon the body.

105
00:06:53,840 --> 00:06:56,900
Aristotle would categorize that as compulsory behavior.

106
00:06:57,160 --> 00:06:58,360
You are being pushed.

107
00:06:59,320 --> 00:07:01,640
But what happens when we act voluntarily?

108
00:07:02,120 --> 00:07:10,980
Aristotle actually spent a lot of time analyzing situations where the line between voluntary and compulsory gets dangerously blurry.

109
00:07:11,160 --> 00:07:11,360
Yeah.

110
00:07:11,520 --> 00:07:13,560
He had a really great thought experiment for this, right?

111
00:07:13,580 --> 00:07:14,180
He did.

112
00:07:14,180 --> 00:07:20,060
He presented this famous scenario of a ship captain caught in a massive storm.

113
00:07:20,300 --> 00:07:25,340
I want to paint the picture of this because it's so incredibly relatable even today.

114
00:07:26,060 --> 00:07:30,300
You have this merchant captain sailing a heavy ship across the agency.

115
00:07:31,080 --> 00:07:33,680
A sudden, violent squall hits.

116
00:07:33,940 --> 00:07:36,000
The waves are crashing over the deck.

117
00:07:36,380 --> 00:07:38,540
The ship is taking on water fast.

118
00:07:38,980 --> 00:07:41,160
And it's on the verge of capsizing.

119
00:07:41,220 --> 00:07:42,000
You're ready for a death.

120
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:42,560
Exactly.

121
00:07:43,040 --> 00:07:48,060
So to stop the ship from sinking, the captain makes a split-second decision.

122
00:07:48,420 --> 00:07:54,360
He orders the crew to throw all their incredibly valuable cargo overboard into the ocean.

123
00:07:54,520 --> 00:07:56,140
All his wealth just gone.

124
00:07:56,340 --> 00:07:56,680
Right.

125
00:07:57,020 --> 00:08:01,940
Now the storm passes, the ship survives, and they limp back to port.

126
00:08:01,940 --> 00:08:11,640
If you approach that captain and ask, hey, did you throw your livelihood into the sea voluntarily, the captain would probably look at you like you were insane.

127
00:08:11,880 --> 00:08:12,100
Right.

128
00:08:12,160 --> 00:08:12,920
He'd be furious.

129
00:08:13,300 --> 00:08:14,240
He'd say, of course not.

130
00:08:14,300 --> 00:08:15,960
I didn't want to ruin myself financially.

131
00:08:16,100 --> 00:08:17,760
I was forced to do it by the storm.

132
00:08:17,920 --> 00:08:22,560
But Aristotle steps in here and examines the actual mechanics of the event.

133
00:08:22,940 --> 00:08:24,900
Was the captain actually forced?

134
00:08:24,900 --> 00:08:31,700
Did the wind physically grab the captain's hands and compel him to heave the crates over the rail?

135
00:08:32,140 --> 00:08:32,420
No.

136
00:08:32,800 --> 00:08:36,780
The origin of the physical movement was still entirely within the captain.

137
00:08:37,800 --> 00:08:40,460
Aristotle categorizes this as a mixed action.

138
00:08:41,320 --> 00:08:43,080
It is undoubtedly painful.

139
00:08:43,480 --> 00:08:45,580
It is done under extreme duress.

140
00:08:45,900 --> 00:08:49,280
And it goes completely against his long-term desires.

141
00:08:49,620 --> 00:08:49,960
Right.

142
00:08:49,960 --> 00:09:01,800
But at the exact microscopic moment the choice was made, throwing the cargo was the most rational, appropriate thing to do to achieve his immediate goal, which was survival.

143
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:04,740
The principle of movement was internal.

144
00:09:05,260 --> 00:09:07,440
The captain perceived a deadly threat.

145
00:09:07,880 --> 00:09:10,600
He possessed a profound desire to stay alive.

146
00:09:10,780 --> 00:09:14,000
And that internal desire is what moved his physical body.

147
00:09:14,520 --> 00:09:17,280
But here's where Aristotle kind of traps himself.

148
00:09:17,420 --> 00:09:17,640
Yeah.

149
00:09:17,640 --> 00:09:26,520
Because of his own unbreakable rule that absolutely nothing can move itself, he had to engage in some truly staggering mental gymnastics here.

150
00:09:26,640 --> 00:09:27,440
He really did.

151
00:09:27,520 --> 00:09:29,680
He couldn't just say the captain moved himself.

152
00:09:29,940 --> 00:09:33,640
He basically had to conceptually slice the organism in half.

153
00:09:34,060 --> 00:09:39,140
He argued that the animal's soul, or its core desire, acts this unmoved mover.

154
00:09:39,360 --> 00:09:39,660
Yeah.

155
00:09:39,800 --> 00:09:42,380
The soul reaches out toward a specific goal in the environment.

156
00:09:42,380 --> 00:09:51,120
It's like a ghost driving a meat suit.

157
00:09:51,120 --> 00:09:51,720
Exactly.

158
00:09:51,720 --> 00:09:57,920
So, technically, in Aristotle's framework, the soul is pushing the body.

159
00:09:57,920 --> 00:10:06,600
It is two separate parts interacting, which magically preserves his rule that a single unified thing is not moving itself.

160
00:10:06,600 --> 00:10:17,840
And that artificial split between the desiring soul and the mechanical body, that is the foundational crack in our whole understanding of human behavior.

161
00:10:17,840 --> 00:10:26,660
Because if you flash forward a couple of thousand years to the Enlightenment and the scientific revolution, modern science enters the chat.

162
00:10:26,660 --> 00:10:27,600
With a vengeance.

163
00:10:28,020 --> 00:10:28,240
Right.

164
00:10:28,440 --> 00:10:31,820
Isaac Newton formulates his monumental laws of physics.

165
00:10:32,620 --> 00:10:40,440
Post-Newtonian philosophy looks back at Aristotle and says, hey, we agree with your fundamental rule that nothing moves itself.

166
00:10:40,860 --> 00:10:43,380
That aligns perfectly with our new physics.

167
00:10:43,840 --> 00:10:48,840
But we're absolutely throwing out this mystical idea of the soul reaching toward a goal.

168
00:10:48,840 --> 00:10:51,920
They completely purged the universe of purpose.

169
00:10:52,140 --> 00:10:52,480
They did.

170
00:10:52,840 --> 00:10:57,480
Aristotle originally had four different types of causes to explain why things happen.

171
00:10:58,100 --> 00:11:07,040
He had final cause, which was the ultimate goal or purpose of an action, and formal cause, which was the underlying structure or pattern of a thing.

172
00:11:07,320 --> 00:11:09,600
But Newtonian physics was ruthless.

173
00:11:09,900 --> 00:11:10,600
Oh, completely.

174
00:11:11,220 --> 00:11:16,500
It stripped everything down to just one acceptable type of causality, efficient cause.

175
00:11:16,500 --> 00:11:20,820
This is the ultimate billiard ball model of the universe.

176
00:11:21,060 --> 00:11:25,380
Reality is nothing but tiny inert atoms crashing into each other.

177
00:11:25,500 --> 00:11:27,060
Just dead matter bumping around.

178
00:11:27,180 --> 00:11:27,440
Right.

179
00:11:27,940 --> 00:11:29,940
A cue ball strikes an eight ball.

180
00:11:30,120 --> 00:11:34,840
The kinetic energy transfers in a split second, and the eight ball rolls away.

181
00:11:35,700 --> 00:11:41,040
The universe is just a giant, meaningless, mathematically predictable game of pool.

182
00:11:41,040 --> 00:11:47,620
Everything that happens is merely the result of external forces bumping into dead matter.

183
00:11:47,860 --> 00:11:50,920
Okay, let's stop and really look at the implications of that.

184
00:11:51,060 --> 00:11:51,240
Okay.

185
00:11:51,400 --> 00:11:52,820
Because it's actually crazy.

186
00:11:53,320 --> 00:11:59,280
If we are forced to view the human brain and the human body like a cue stick hitting a cue ball,

187
00:11:59,720 --> 00:12:04,380
how on earth do we explain the most basic realities of human existence?

188
00:12:04,560 --> 00:12:05,860
It gets really difficult.

189
00:12:06,100 --> 00:12:06,320
Right.

190
00:12:06,320 --> 00:12:08,520
How do we explain long-term planning?

191
00:12:08,760 --> 00:12:12,560
Let's say I make a decision today that I want to become a neurosurgeon.

192
00:12:13,280 --> 00:12:18,200
That intention has to somehow guide my daily actions for the next 15 years.

193
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:25,140
I have to study, take exams, skip parties, apply to medical school, and survive residency.

194
00:12:25,400 --> 00:12:27,260
That's a lot of sustained action.

195
00:12:27,260 --> 00:12:28,260
Exactly.

196
00:12:28,980 --> 00:12:36,260
But a cue stick doesn't follow the ball down the felt table to continuously guide it around obstacles

197
00:12:36,260 --> 00:12:38,800
and gently shepherd it into the corner pocket.

198
00:12:39,200 --> 00:12:46,200
It just transfers its energy in one violent split second collision and immediately disconnects.

199
00:12:46,460 --> 00:12:53,500
The friction you are feeling right now is the exact fatal flaw of the modern theory of causality.

200
00:12:53,500 --> 00:12:58,540
In philosophical terms, we refer to this as the bump-and-run model.

201
00:12:58,900 --> 00:12:59,420
Bump-and-run.

202
00:12:59,460 --> 00:12:59,680
Yeah.

203
00:13:00,200 --> 00:13:03,040
Modern science basically built a trap for itself.

204
00:13:03,720 --> 00:13:10,440
By permanently banning the concept of self-cause and by completely outlawing the idea of a standing,

205
00:13:10,940 --> 00:13:17,480
top-down constraint, like a conscious goal that continuously oversees and guides a complex system

206
00:13:17,480 --> 00:13:24,360
over time, they left themselves with no vocabulary to explain how an intention actually sustains an action.

207
00:13:24,720 --> 00:13:25,720
They just threw it out.

208
00:13:25,840 --> 00:13:26,640
They had to.

209
00:13:26,900 --> 00:13:31,320
They were forced to imagine a human intention as nothing more than a mental cue stick.

210
00:13:31,320 --> 00:13:37,140
It flares up, it strikes the motor neurons, the muscles twitch, and the intention instantly disengages,

211
00:13:37,620 --> 00:13:40,280
leaving the body to blindly carry out the momentum.

212
00:13:40,280 --> 00:13:47,540
Which is obviously demonstrably false to absolutely anyone who has ever lived a human life.

213
00:13:48,120 --> 00:13:54,180
I mean, if I am threading a needle, my intention to thread that needle is actively managing the

214
00:13:54,180 --> 00:13:57,420
micro-tremors in my fingers every single millisecond.

215
00:13:57,780 --> 00:13:59,580
It's not a one-time push.

216
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:00,420
Exactly.

217
00:14:00,420 --> 00:14:07,580
But instead of realizing their mechanical billiard ball model was broken, scientists and philosophers

218
00:14:07,580 --> 00:14:11,920
in the early 20th century decided to just double down.

219
00:14:12,120 --> 00:14:13,660
They really dug their heels in.

220
00:14:13,800 --> 00:14:14,400
They did.

221
00:14:14,540 --> 00:14:19,540
If the mind didn't fit the physics, they decided to just throw the mind in the garbage.

222
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:24,880
And that leads us directly into the incredibly bizarre era of behaviorism.

223
00:14:24,980 --> 00:14:25,440
Oh man.

224
00:14:25,960 --> 00:14:26,480
Behaviorism?

225
00:14:26,480 --> 00:14:32,000
Yeah, behaviorism was really an act of desperation because researchers couldn't figure out how

226
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:38,320
a mental intention, this invisible weightless ghost in the machine, could possibly push physical

227
00:14:38,320 --> 00:14:41,820
heavy muscles without violating the conservation of energy.

228
00:14:42,440 --> 00:14:46,120
They just decided that the internal mind was scientifically irrelevant.

229
00:14:46,340 --> 00:14:46,940
Just ignore it?

230
00:14:46,980 --> 00:14:47,460
Pretty much.

231
00:14:47,800 --> 00:14:53,560
They leaned heavily on the philosopher David Hume, specifically his concept of constant conjunction.

232
00:14:53,960 --> 00:14:55,980
Right, Hume was like the ultimate skeptic.

233
00:14:55,980 --> 00:15:00,300
He basically argued that humans can't actually see causality.

234
00:15:01,040 --> 00:15:04,380
We can never observe the invisible force of cause and effect.

235
00:15:05,380 --> 00:15:10,820
All we can actually observe is one event happening followed immediately by another event.

236
00:15:10,940 --> 00:15:13,580
Over and over, event A, then event B.

237
00:15:14,040 --> 00:15:16,620
A bell rings and a dog drools.

238
00:15:17,180 --> 00:15:22,940
We assume the bell caused the drool, but strictly speaking, we only see the conjunction of the two

239
00:15:22,940 --> 00:15:23,380
events.

240
00:15:23,380 --> 00:15:26,160
So the behaviorists took this and ran with it.

241
00:15:26,240 --> 00:15:29,200
They said, stop worrying about what the dog is thinking.

242
00:15:29,400 --> 00:15:31,300
Stop worrying about the ghost in the machine.

243
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:36,220
Science is only about observable inputs and observable outputs.

244
00:15:37,220 --> 00:15:38,380
Stimulus and response.

245
00:15:39,160 --> 00:15:42,740
Which leads to a terrifying definition of human life if you think about it.

246
00:15:42,740 --> 00:15:49,560
Under strict behaviorism, human action is reduced to nothing more than uttering the correct sequence

247
00:15:49,560 --> 00:15:55,660
of words or executing the correct sequence of physical movements under suitable environmental

248
00:15:55,660 --> 00:15:56,460
circumstances.

249
00:15:57,100 --> 00:15:57,600
That's it.

250
00:15:58,300 --> 00:15:59,840
Intent is a total myth.

251
00:16:00,020 --> 00:16:02,220
It completely erases the inner life.

252
00:16:02,560 --> 00:16:03,140
It does.

253
00:16:03,140 --> 00:16:05,800
There was this philosopher, J.L.

254
00:16:05,880 --> 00:16:11,020
Austin, who really championed this with his performative theory of action.

255
00:16:12,080 --> 00:16:18,220
He argued that certain massive life events, like getting married, are not about your internal

256
00:16:18,220 --> 00:16:21,540
emotional state or your conscious intentions at all.

257
00:16:21,600 --> 00:16:21,860
Right.

258
00:16:21,920 --> 00:16:27,420
Getting married is simply the physical act of uttering a specific script of words in a specific

259
00:16:27,420 --> 00:16:29,340
socially recognized setting.

260
00:16:29,340 --> 00:16:37,640
But when you try to apply this theory to the real world, it results in absolute comical disaster.

261
00:16:38,080 --> 00:16:42,320
There are two incredible examples from the text that highlight this perfectly.

262
00:16:42,480 --> 00:16:44,340
Oh, these examples are so good.

263
00:16:44,460 --> 00:16:45,040
They're crazy.

264
00:16:45,520 --> 00:16:49,860
So the first is a scenario about a woman, let's just call her Hannah.

265
00:16:50,360 --> 00:16:52,000
Hannah is at a lively party.

266
00:16:52,160 --> 00:16:55,640
She's having a few drinks, laughing, joking around with her friends.

267
00:16:55,640 --> 00:17:01,540
A guy at the party, completely playing along with the joke, slides a ring onto her finger

268
00:17:01,540 --> 00:17:06,120
and jokingly recites an ancient traditional Jewish wedding phrase.

269
00:17:06,380 --> 00:17:07,240
Just goofing off.

270
00:17:07,360 --> 00:17:07,620
Right.

271
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:09,260
Everyone in the circle is laughing.

272
00:17:09,400 --> 00:17:10,360
The guy knows it's a joke.

273
00:17:10,480 --> 00:17:11,520
Hannah knows it's a joke.

274
00:17:12,240 --> 00:17:17,620
But sitting quietly on the couch nearby is an actual rabbi who happens to be a strict

275
00:17:17,620 --> 00:17:19,340
expert in rabbinical law.

276
00:17:19,420 --> 00:17:19,900
Yes.

277
00:17:19,900 --> 00:17:26,860
The rabbi stands up, walks over, and says, excuse me, all the objective conditions for

278
00:17:26,860 --> 00:17:28,240
a marriage were just met.

279
00:17:28,960 --> 00:17:34,780
A ring of value was presented, the correct words were spoken flawlessly, and there are

280
00:17:34,780 --> 00:17:36,260
valid witnesses present.

281
00:17:37,080 --> 00:17:42,660
Regardless of your internal feelings, by the letter of the law, you two are now officially

282
00:17:42,660 --> 00:17:44,040
legally married.

283
00:17:44,040 --> 00:17:49,000
It perfectly highlights the absolute absurdity of ignoring intent.

284
00:17:49,540 --> 00:17:52,920
And the crazy thing is, it's not just the theoretical party trick.

285
00:17:53,140 --> 00:17:56,540
It happens in the real world with devastating consequences.

286
00:17:56,800 --> 00:17:57,020
Yes.

287
00:17:57,140 --> 00:18:01,000
The second example is an actual documented news story from Pakistan.

288
00:18:01,820 --> 00:18:07,160
A real-life husband and wife were working as actors on a television soap opera.

289
00:18:07,600 --> 00:18:11,960
They were on set, the cameras were rolling, and they were playing their fictional characters.

290
00:18:12,180 --> 00:18:13,640
They're literally doing a job.

291
00:18:13,640 --> 00:18:14,040
Right.

292
00:18:14,280 --> 00:18:19,620
During a highly dramatic scene, the script called for the husband to recite the traditional

293
00:18:19,620 --> 00:18:23,640
Islamic divorce declaration saying, I divorce you three times.

294
00:18:24,120 --> 00:18:25,220
They're acting.

295
00:18:25,680 --> 00:18:29,220
They're on a soundstage surrounded by boom mics and lighting raves.

296
00:18:29,240 --> 00:18:30,500
But the words were said.

297
00:18:30,640 --> 00:18:31,260
Exactly.

298
00:18:32,020 --> 00:18:37,840
A group of strict religious clerics watched the broadcast and issued a real-life ruling.

299
00:18:38,560 --> 00:18:43,480
They stated that because the specific words were articulated, the real-life

300
00:18:43,480 --> 00:18:47,220
marriage between the actors was immediately and officially dissolved.

301
00:18:47,620 --> 00:18:47,840
Yeah.

302
00:18:48,500 --> 00:18:53,560
The clerics even warned them that continuing to live together in their own home constituted

303
00:18:53,560 --> 00:18:54,140
adultery.

304
00:18:54,140 --> 00:18:55,140
It's horrifying.

305
00:18:56,140 --> 00:19:02,020
But why do those outcomes provoke such a visceral reaction of wrongness in us?

306
00:19:02,160 --> 00:19:04,960
Why do we immediately recoil from those rulings?

307
00:19:05,080 --> 00:19:05,940
Because it's insane.

308
00:19:06,100 --> 00:19:06,580
It is.

309
00:19:06,700 --> 00:19:13,440
It is because our fundamental human intuition recognizes that behaviorism is structurally bankrupt.

310
00:19:13,860 --> 00:19:18,720
You simply cannot reduce a human action to merely conforming to a pattern of behavior.

311
00:19:18,720 --> 00:19:23,220
Internal awareness and intent are not optional add-ons.

312
00:19:23,360 --> 00:19:25,600
They are the core architecture of an action.

313
00:19:26,100 --> 00:19:32,020
Aristotle, thousands of years ago, understood this way better than the 20th century behaviorists.

314
00:19:32,180 --> 00:19:34,160
He called it the reason of ignorance.

315
00:19:34,460 --> 00:19:35,720
The reason of ignorance.

316
00:19:36,040 --> 00:19:36,300
Okay.

317
00:19:36,440 --> 00:19:37,060
Unpack that.

318
00:19:37,060 --> 00:19:42,540
If Hannah was genuinely ignorant of the legal gravity of the ritual she was participating

319
00:19:42,540 --> 00:19:50,040
in, or if the Pakistani actors were operating under the explicit shared cognitive frame of

320
00:19:50,040 --> 00:19:57,640
a fictional performance, their internal intent drastically diverged from the external social

321
00:19:57,640 --> 00:19:58,180
outcome.

322
00:19:58,420 --> 00:19:58,500
Yeah.

323
00:19:58,920 --> 00:20:04,800
The behaviorist looks at the tape and says, well, the audio pattern matches the legal requirement.

324
00:20:04,800 --> 00:20:06,440
Therefore, the action occurred.

325
00:20:06,820 --> 00:20:12,720
But we know that an action without the animating force of intent is just empty physics.

326
00:20:12,940 --> 00:20:13,060
Okay.

327
00:20:13,160 --> 00:20:16,700
Let me play devil's advocate here because I really want to push this to the breaking point.

328
00:20:16,780 --> 00:20:17,280
Go for it.

329
00:20:17,640 --> 00:20:24,700
What if the behavior doesn't just match a legal script, but it physically produces a perfect

330
00:20:24,700 --> 00:20:26,400
outcome by total accident?

331
00:20:27,420 --> 00:20:30,540
Let's say I'm sitting at a desk with a photograph of a house.

332
00:20:30,540 --> 00:20:37,340
I take a piece of tracing paper, and with deep concentration, I intentionally trace every

333
00:20:37,340 --> 00:20:39,120
line until I have a perfect replica.

334
00:20:39,240 --> 00:20:40,400
Hey, a deliberate action.

335
00:20:40,780 --> 00:20:41,020
Right.

336
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:42,920
Now, imagine another scenario.

337
00:20:43,300 --> 00:20:44,500
I am blindfolded.

338
00:20:44,620 --> 00:20:48,800
I have a pen in my hand, and I am having a random muscle spasm.

339
00:20:49,000 --> 00:20:51,680
My hand is just violently jerking around on the paper.

340
00:20:52,280 --> 00:20:59,380
But, against all astronomical odds, the ink happens to land in the exact shape of that identical

341
00:20:59,380 --> 00:20:59,860
house.

342
00:20:59,860 --> 00:21:02,260
A one-in-a-trillion chance.

343
00:21:02,380 --> 00:21:02,820
Exactly.

344
00:21:03,520 --> 00:21:09,000
To a pure behaviorist, who only looks at the final output, they both produced a house.

345
00:21:10,020 --> 00:21:14,580
Can behaviorism actually differentiate between the argus and the spasm?

346
00:21:14,860 --> 00:21:19,500
That is the exact thought experiment that shattered the behaviorist consensus.

347
00:21:20,540 --> 00:21:23,840
Philosophers like Larry Wright really grappled with this paradox.

348
00:21:23,840 --> 00:21:31,380
How do you objectively distinguish between purposeful action and cosmic coincidence if you absolutely

349
00:21:31,380 --> 00:21:33,040
refuse to look inside the mind?

350
00:21:33,160 --> 00:21:33,360
Right.

351
00:21:33,500 --> 00:21:33,980
You can't.

352
00:21:34,060 --> 00:21:39,640
To illustrate how impossible this is, philosophers introduced the chess-playing Martian scenario.

353
00:21:39,740 --> 00:21:40,580
I love this one.

354
00:21:40,580 --> 00:21:45,440
Imagine an alien spacecraft lands on Earth.

355
00:21:45,440 --> 00:21:46,800
A Martian steps out.

356
00:21:47,240 --> 00:21:57,900
This creature has absolutely no conceptual framework for games, no understanding of rules, no concept of human competition, and no idea what winning or losing even means.

357
00:21:57,900 --> 00:21:59,640
It's just a totally alien mind.

358
00:21:59,980 --> 00:22:00,300
Right.

359
00:22:00,300 --> 00:22:06,000
The Martian happens to sit down at a table across from a human chess grandmaster.

360
00:22:06,380 --> 00:22:07,980
The grandmaster moves a pawn.

361
00:22:08,460 --> 00:22:16,460
The Martian, perhaps responding to a random electromagnetic fluctuation in its environment, reaches out and moves the knight.

362
00:22:16,460 --> 00:22:17,440
Just a twitch.

363
00:22:17,600 --> 00:22:18,340
Just a twitch.

364
00:22:18,660 --> 00:22:19,820
The grandmaster counters.

365
00:22:20,280 --> 00:22:27,500
The Martian, again randomly twitching, happens to execute the exact mathematically perfect counter move.

366
00:22:28,060 --> 00:22:34,860
This continues for 40 moves until the Martian accidentally delivers a flawless checkmate.

367
00:22:35,660 --> 00:22:38,840
The question is, is the Martian playing chess?

368
00:22:39,360 --> 00:22:39,800
No.

369
00:22:40,280 --> 00:22:41,040
Of course not.

370
00:22:41,340 --> 00:22:45,320
It's just manipulating carved pieces of wood on a checkered board.

371
00:22:45,320 --> 00:22:48,080
It has no idea what a bishop is or what a king is.

372
00:22:48,280 --> 00:22:48,760
Precisely.

373
00:22:48,960 --> 00:22:55,940
And this destroys behaviorism because it highlights the monumental difference between conforming to a rule and following a rule.

374
00:22:56,040 --> 00:22:58,000
Ah, conforming versus following.

375
00:22:58,120 --> 00:22:58,420
Yes.

376
00:22:59,260 --> 00:23:04,260
The Martian's physical movements conform to the rules of chess by pure statistical anomaly.

377
00:23:04,840 --> 00:23:13,440
But to follow a rule requires a conscious entity to deliberately pattern their ongoing behavior after an internal representation of that rule.

378
00:23:13,440 --> 00:23:15,660
It requires a mind holding a goal.

379
00:23:15,660 --> 00:23:25,840
The behaviorists tried their hardest to banish the ghost in the machine, but it turns out the ghost is the only thing that makes the machine's movements meaningful.

380
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:30,020
Okay, so, the behaviorist detour was a complete failure.

381
00:23:31,100 --> 00:23:32,380
We are forced to retreat.

382
00:23:33,060 --> 00:23:38,800
We have to admit that our internal invisible intentions must be the cause of our physical actions.

383
00:23:38,960 --> 00:23:40,020
We need the ghost.

384
00:23:40,180 --> 00:23:40,980
We need the ghost.

385
00:23:41,080 --> 00:23:41,300
Yeah.

386
00:23:41,300 --> 00:23:51,040
But, and this is a massive but, we are still shackled to that broken Newtonian billiard ball theory of cause and effect.

387
00:23:51,160 --> 00:23:51,400
Yeah.

388
00:23:51,520 --> 00:23:56,100
We still have to explain how the mental cue stick hits the physical cue ball.

389
00:23:56,140 --> 00:23:58,000
Right, the physics still don't make sense.

390
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:06,440
And trying to cram human intention into Newtonian physics leads to my absolute favorite philosophical trap in this entire deep dive.

391
00:24:06,960 --> 00:24:10,180
It is known as the problem of the wayward causal chain.

392
00:24:10,280 --> 00:24:11,720
Ah, yes.

393
00:24:12,040 --> 00:24:16,320
Roderick Chisholm's legendary thought experiment about the nervous nephew.

394
00:24:17,160 --> 00:24:20,860
This is where the old model of physics finally just breaks in half.

395
00:24:21,060 --> 00:24:22,720
It is so darkly brilliant.

396
00:24:22,940 --> 00:24:25,120
Okay, let's set the stage for this one.

397
00:24:25,120 --> 00:24:26,680
Imagine a young man.

398
00:24:27,000 --> 00:24:29,660
He has an extremely wealthy elderly uncle.

399
00:24:30,480 --> 00:24:36,240
The nephew is greedy, he's impatient, and he decides he wants his massive inheritance right now.

400
00:24:36,520 --> 00:24:37,740
A classic motive.

401
00:24:38,020 --> 00:24:38,420
Classic.

402
00:24:39,020 --> 00:24:45,820
He sits in his apartment and forms a crystal clear, deeply conscious, premeditated intention.

403
00:24:46,340 --> 00:24:50,080
I am going to get in my car, drive to my uncle's house, and run him over.

404
00:24:50,720 --> 00:24:52,260
He has the motive, he has the plan.

405
00:24:52,440 --> 00:24:54,860
So he goes downstairs and gets behind the wheel.

406
00:24:54,860 --> 00:24:56,480
The intention has formed.

407
00:24:57,160 --> 00:24:57,560
Right.

408
00:24:57,980 --> 00:25:05,020
But the sheer weight of forming this dark, murderous intention completely overwhelms his nervous system.

409
00:25:05,540 --> 00:25:07,380
He becomes incredibly agitated.

410
00:25:07,900 --> 00:25:09,540
He is sweating profusely.

411
00:25:09,680 --> 00:25:11,280
His hands are violently shaking.

412
00:25:11,740 --> 00:25:13,640
His heart is hammering in his chest.

413
00:25:13,660 --> 00:25:15,280
He's having a full panic attack.

414
00:25:15,460 --> 00:25:16,000
Exactly.

415
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:23,860
He is so consumed and distracted by the horror of his own plan that he completely loses control of his vehicle.

416
00:25:24,640 --> 00:25:31,420
The car violently swerves off the road, hops the curb, and accidentally plows into a random pedestrian walking on the sidewalk.

417
00:25:31,420 --> 00:25:40,580
The nephew, horrified, jumps out of the wrecked car, looks down, and realizes the pedestrian he just killed is his rich uncle.

418
00:25:40,580 --> 00:25:42,000
The trap is set.

419
00:25:42,200 --> 00:25:42,320
Yeah.

420
00:25:42,400 --> 00:25:46,020
So we have to ask the ultimate philosophical and legal question here.

421
00:25:46,480 --> 00:25:48,360
Did the nephew murder his uncle?

422
00:25:48,620 --> 00:25:50,380
Did he perform the action of killing?

423
00:25:50,800 --> 00:25:59,880
See, if you are forced to use the standard billiard ball model of causality, the horrifying answer is technically yes.

424
00:26:00,080 --> 00:26:00,400
Right.

425
00:26:00,700 --> 00:26:01,700
The math checks out.

426
00:26:01,820 --> 00:26:02,380
It does.

427
00:26:02,500 --> 00:26:02,700
Yeah.

428
00:26:02,700 --> 00:26:04,100
Let's trace the physics.

429
00:26:05,320 --> 00:26:08,380
The nephew had an internal intention to kill his uncle.

430
00:26:09,600 --> 00:26:16,280
That intention, the cue stick, struck his nervous system, causing a state of severe agitation, the cue ball.

431
00:26:16,940 --> 00:26:27,260
That agitation caused his hands to jerk the steering wheel, which caused the car to swerve, which caused the blunt force trauma that resulted in the death of the uncle.

432
00:26:27,800 --> 00:26:29,220
The eight ball in the corner pocket.

433
00:26:29,240 --> 00:26:30,740
The causal chain is unbroken.

434
00:26:31,140 --> 00:26:31,600
Exactly.

435
00:26:31,600 --> 00:26:35,020
Event A caused event B caused event C.

436
00:26:35,560 --> 00:26:37,860
Philosophers were terrified by this loophole.

437
00:26:38,320 --> 00:26:45,440
Arthur Danto, a highly influential thinker, tried to patch the hole by introducing a new requirement called semantic fit.

438
00:26:45,640 --> 00:26:46,420
Semantic fit?

439
00:26:46,520 --> 00:26:46,700
Yeah.

440
00:26:46,980 --> 00:26:56,900
He argued that an event only qualifies as a genuine action if the final real-world outcome matches the original semantic representation in the person's bed.

441
00:26:57,420 --> 00:26:59,020
He thought this would save the theory.

442
00:26:59,020 --> 00:27:01,900
But apply Danto's rule to the nephew.

443
00:27:02,420 --> 00:27:05,240
The nephew's internal representation was a dead uncle.

444
00:27:05,780 --> 00:27:08,520
The final outcome in the real world is a dead uncle.

445
00:27:08,960 --> 00:27:11,140
The semantic fit is literally perfect.

446
00:27:11,540 --> 00:27:12,180
Exactly.

447
00:27:12,720 --> 00:27:24,820
Yet every single fiber of our human intuition screams that this was a vehicular manslaughter wrapped in a cosmic irony, not a successful execution of a murder plot.

448
00:27:24,820 --> 00:27:25,820
Why?

449
00:27:26,200 --> 00:27:28,280
Because the nephew lost control.

450
00:27:28,780 --> 00:27:29,280
Yes.

451
00:27:29,600 --> 00:27:34,760
The intention started the chain reaction, but it completely disconnected midstream.

452
00:27:34,920 --> 00:27:36,740
The cue stick slipped off the ball.

453
00:27:36,920 --> 00:27:38,420
That is the crucial insight.

454
00:27:38,420 --> 00:27:43,080
The intention did not actively guide the behavior to its completion.

455
00:27:43,400 --> 00:27:48,180
It acted as a blind, momentary trigger, not an ongoing constraint.

456
00:27:48,800 --> 00:27:51,340
Think back to your tracing example with the house.

457
00:27:51,580 --> 00:28:03,060
If you want to trace the picture, your intention to trace has to continuously, actively guide the micro-movements of your hand, millimeter by millimeter, correcting for errors in real time.

458
00:28:03,060 --> 00:28:04,960
Right, I'm watching the line as I draw it.

459
00:28:05,020 --> 00:28:05,500
Exactly.

460
00:28:05,940 --> 00:28:10,940
It cannot just violently shove your hand across the desk and hope the ink miraculously forms a roof.

461
00:28:11,180 --> 00:28:14,220
The standard causal model only allows for pushing.

462
00:28:14,620 --> 00:28:17,600
It has absolutely no mechanism for guiding.

463
00:28:18,020 --> 00:28:20,340
So philosophy has essentially hit a brick wall.

464
00:28:20,820 --> 00:28:26,780
The ancient physics don't work, Newtonian physics don't work, and behaviorism is a joke.

465
00:28:27,320 --> 00:28:28,840
Where do we even go from here?

466
00:28:28,840 --> 00:28:36,880
The brilliant pivot here is that we have to stop talking to philosophers and physicists who study moving mass.

467
00:28:37,380 --> 00:28:37,460
Right.

468
00:28:37,620 --> 00:28:40,960
We have to cross the campus and talk to communications engineers.

469
00:28:41,380 --> 00:28:44,080
We have to dive into information theory.

470
00:28:44,580 --> 00:28:47,080
This is where the paradigm shift actually happens.

471
00:28:47,240 --> 00:28:47,800
It is.

472
00:28:48,200 --> 00:28:55,080
In the 1940s, a mathematician named Claude Shannon, working at Bell Labs, developed information theory.

473
00:28:55,080 --> 00:28:59,020
He wasn't trying to solve the riddle of free will.

474
00:28:59,420 --> 00:29:08,720
He was just trying to figure out how to transmit voice messages over long copper telephone lines without the signal turning into static.

475
00:29:09,060 --> 00:29:16,120
But it turns out the mathematics of signal transmission are the exact tools we need to solve the philosopher's dead end.

476
00:29:16,620 --> 00:29:17,060
Completely.

477
00:29:17,060 --> 00:29:22,560
Because information theory completely abandons the idea of objects crashing into each other.

478
00:29:22,900 --> 00:29:24,780
It doesn't care about force or mass.

479
00:29:24,980 --> 00:29:30,220
It cares entirely about tracking the flow of a signal from a source to a destination.

480
00:29:30,580 --> 00:29:33,660
Yeah, let's ground this math in a story because it can get abstract.

481
00:29:34,240 --> 00:29:41,340
There is a fantastic example formulated by the philosopher Fred Dretzky involving an office worker named Herman.

482
00:29:41,880 --> 00:29:43,320
Oh, I'll walk through this one.

483
00:29:43,320 --> 00:29:46,880
So imagine a corporate office with eight employees.

484
00:29:47,760 --> 00:29:56,520
The boss comes in and says, hey, one of you has to stay late on Friday to do this incredibly tedious, nasty inventory task.

485
00:29:56,820 --> 00:29:59,820
I don't care who, you figure it out and let me know.

486
00:29:59,900 --> 00:30:01,520
Standard, terrible boss.

487
00:30:01,720 --> 00:30:02,200
Exactly.

488
00:30:02,200 --> 00:30:13,620
So the eight employees sit in a conference room and they decide to make it fair by flipping coins to eliminate people until there's only one loser left.

489
00:30:13,920 --> 00:30:15,840
Let's do the math on this really quick.

490
00:30:16,120 --> 00:30:17,620
You start with eight possibilities.

491
00:30:18,020 --> 00:30:22,160
You flip a coin, heads or tails, and you eliminate half the room.

492
00:30:22,940 --> 00:30:23,640
Now you have four possibilities.

493
00:30:24,300 --> 00:30:25,540
At least one bit of information.

494
00:30:25,800 --> 00:30:26,020
Right.

495
00:30:26,280 --> 00:30:28,960
You flip again, eliminating half the remaining people.

496
00:30:29,340 --> 00:30:30,580
Now you have two possibilities.

497
00:30:30,680 --> 00:30:31,460
That's two bits.

498
00:30:31,460 --> 00:30:35,420
You flip a third time and you're left with one single loser.

499
00:30:35,840 --> 00:30:36,680
That's three bits.

500
00:30:36,780 --> 00:30:42,440
It takes exactly three bits of information to reduce eight possibilities down to a single certainty.

501
00:30:43,180 --> 00:30:45,940
And the loser, sadly, is Herman.

502
00:30:46,380 --> 00:30:47,360
Poor Herman.

503
00:30:47,980 --> 00:30:50,740
So we have established our starting point.

504
00:30:50,880 --> 00:30:58,920
We have a source, the coin flipping process in the conference room, that has successfully generated exactly three bits of information.

505
00:30:58,920 --> 00:31:08,060
Now, that information has to flow across the environment to reach its destination, which is the boss's desk.

506
00:31:08,240 --> 00:31:08,600
Right.

507
00:31:08,800 --> 00:31:12,880
So let's look at scenario A, which we'll call the careful messenger.

508
00:31:12,880 --> 00:31:21,280
The employees write Herman on a piece of paper, fold it up, and hand it to a very diligent, careful intern.

509
00:31:21,800 --> 00:31:26,860
The intern walks down the halls, knocks on the boss's door, and hands over the note.

510
00:31:27,260 --> 00:31:29,600
The bog opens it and reads Herman.

511
00:31:29,600 --> 00:31:30,600
Perfect transmission.

512
00:31:30,600 --> 00:31:31,040
Perfect transmission.

513
00:31:31,320 --> 00:31:31,720
Exactly.

514
00:31:32,440 --> 00:31:40,060
In this scenario, the three bits of information generated at the source perfectly equal the three bits of information received at the destination.

515
00:31:40,740 --> 00:31:41,920
The flow is unbroken.

516
00:31:41,920 --> 00:31:46,760
But then Dretzky introduces scenario B, which is the careless messenger.

517
00:31:47,300 --> 00:31:49,860
The exact same process happens in the conference room.

518
00:31:50,040 --> 00:31:50,660
Herman loses.

519
00:31:51,180 --> 00:31:55,280
They write his name on a note and hand it to a careless, easily distracted intern.

520
00:31:56,060 --> 00:32:03,440
As this intern is walking down the hall, he trips and the note slips out of his hand and falls directly into an active paper shredder.

521
00:32:03,780 --> 00:32:04,700
The note is gone.

522
00:32:05,560 --> 00:32:06,040
Destroyed.

523
00:32:06,280 --> 00:32:07,620
The intern panics.

524
00:32:07,620 --> 00:32:13,640
He knows there are eight employees in that department, but he has absolutely no idea who lost the coin toss.

525
00:32:14,180 --> 00:32:16,360
He knows he'll be fired if he doesn't deliver a name.

526
00:32:17,120 --> 00:32:20,860
So in a moment of desperation, he decides to just guess.

527
00:32:21,500 --> 00:32:24,680
He pulls out a blank piece of paper, randomly writes,

528
00:32:24,980 --> 00:32:28,540
Herman, walks into the boss's office, and hands it over.

529
00:32:29,260 --> 00:32:30,600
Now look at the end result here.

530
00:32:30,940 --> 00:32:32,420
The boss opens the note.

531
00:32:32,800 --> 00:32:33,540
It says Herman.

532
00:32:33,540 --> 00:32:38,300
The observable outcome in the room is identical to scenario A.

533
00:32:38,820 --> 00:32:41,260
The boss believes Herman is doing the inventory.

534
00:32:41,980 --> 00:32:46,840
But structurally, something is profoundly, deeply broken here.

535
00:32:47,120 --> 00:32:51,880
Because absolutely zero information actually flowed from the source to the destination.

536
00:32:52,580 --> 00:32:56,220
The three bits of information from the coin flip died in the shredder.

537
00:32:56,860 --> 00:33:01,940
The Herman that arrived on the desk was generated entirely by the intern's random panic.

538
00:33:01,940 --> 00:33:10,480
Information theory gives us the precise mathematical vocabulary to articulate why scenario B feels like a lie, even though the outcome is correct.

539
00:33:11,140 --> 00:33:16,940
In Shannon's framework, there are two primary enemies that destroy the flow of information across a channel.

540
00:33:17,500 --> 00:33:19,820
They are called equivocation and noise.

541
00:33:20,160 --> 00:33:22,900
These are critical concepts, so let's define them carefully.

542
00:33:23,060 --> 00:33:23,300
Sure.

543
00:33:23,300 --> 00:33:31,760
Equivocation is information that is successfully generated at the source, but gets lost or destroyed in transit.

544
00:33:32,140 --> 00:33:33,940
It never reaches the destination.

545
00:33:34,180 --> 00:33:35,920
It is a drop in the signal.

546
00:33:36,900 --> 00:33:39,740
Noise, on the other hand, is the exact opposite.

547
00:33:40,520 --> 00:33:46,420
Noise is rogue information that appears at the destination, but it did not originate from the source.

548
00:33:46,540 --> 00:33:49,680
It was introduced into the channel somewhere along the journey.

549
00:33:49,680 --> 00:33:53,300
I think the clearest way to visualize this is through a car radio.

550
00:33:53,860 --> 00:33:54,940
Oh, that's a good analogy.

551
00:33:55,140 --> 00:33:55,240
Yeah.

552
00:33:55,320 --> 00:34:00,220
Imagine you are driving and you tune into the local news station.

553
00:34:00,880 --> 00:34:06,340
The announcer at the station, who is the source, says, there will be rain on Sunday.

554
00:34:06,900 --> 00:34:12,660
But your car is driving through a tunnel and the antenna picks up a bunch of static, so you hear, there will be rain on Sunday.

555
00:34:13,180 --> 00:34:14,360
Snap, crackle, pop.

556
00:34:14,600 --> 00:34:14,900
Right.

557
00:34:14,900 --> 00:34:17,280
That static is pure noise.

558
00:34:17,800 --> 00:34:21,500
It is extra garbage information that the announcer never spoke.

559
00:34:22,360 --> 00:34:27,060
However, despite the noise, the core message survives.

560
00:34:27,900 --> 00:34:30,180
You still noted an umbrella on Sunday.

561
00:34:30,900 --> 00:34:34,260
The channel has noise, but it does not have equivocation.

562
00:34:34,660 --> 00:34:36,040
The signal pushed through.

563
00:34:36,240 --> 00:34:38,720
But consider a slight variation on that.

564
00:34:38,720 --> 00:34:45,580
What if that burst of static happens at the exact millisecond the announcer is speaking the day of the week?

565
00:34:46,180 --> 00:34:49,980
The radio broadcasts, there will be rain on loud static day-day.

566
00:34:50,380 --> 00:34:52,520
Now you have a catastrophic problem.

567
00:34:52,660 --> 00:34:53,120
Exactly.

568
00:34:53,440 --> 00:34:54,080
Is it Sunday?

569
00:34:54,340 --> 00:34:54,900
Is it Monday?

570
00:34:55,040 --> 00:34:55,540
You don't know.

571
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:02,600
The static, the noise, was so perfectly placed that it obliterated the crucial difference between the two days.

572
00:35:03,120 --> 00:35:06,800
The information generated at the source was destroyed in transit.

573
00:35:06,800 --> 00:35:11,220
In this case, the noise directly caused equivocation.

574
00:35:11,900 --> 00:35:12,980
The signal is dead.

575
00:35:13,920 --> 00:35:16,480
This is the moment where all the pieces lock together.

576
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:24,220
We can take this exact mathematics from telephone lines and radio antennas and apply it directly to the nervous nephew in his car.

577
00:35:24,320 --> 00:35:25,540
Yes, let's map it out.

578
00:35:25,700 --> 00:35:25,960
Okay.

579
00:35:26,400 --> 00:35:31,500
The nephew's conscious, murderous intention inside his brain is the source.

580
00:35:31,500 --> 00:35:36,640
The steering wheel and the physical trajectory of the car are the destination.

581
00:35:37,760 --> 00:35:39,720
The intention generates the signal.

582
00:35:40,420 --> 00:35:42,460
Turn the wheel 15 degrees to the right.

583
00:35:42,780 --> 00:35:43,420
Accelerate.

584
00:35:43,900 --> 00:35:44,760
Aim for the uncle.

585
00:35:44,900 --> 00:35:46,560
That's the clear message.

586
00:35:47,060 --> 00:35:49,420
The signal starts traveling down his nervous system.

587
00:35:49,420 --> 00:35:54,460
But suddenly, his extreme existential panic kicks in.

588
00:35:55,120 --> 00:36:04,500
The sweating, the violent shaking of his hands, the erratic hammering of his heart, all of that severe physiological agitation is noise.

589
00:36:05,240 --> 00:36:10,340
It is massive amounts of rogue kinetic energy flooding the channel.

590
00:36:10,340 --> 00:36:14,980
And it is a level of noise that causes total, catastrophic equivocation.

591
00:36:15,800 --> 00:36:22,200
The precise, guided signal of his intention turned 15 degrees right is completely drowned out by the shaking of his hands.

592
00:36:22,680 --> 00:36:24,800
The signal never reaches the steering wheel.

593
00:36:25,320 --> 00:36:29,480
The structural link between the mind and the environment is severed.

594
00:36:29,980 --> 00:36:33,780
The nervous shaking was the careless messenger dropping the note in the shredder.

595
00:36:33,900 --> 00:36:34,380
Exactly.

596
00:36:34,380 --> 00:36:39,580
The uncle still died at the end of the timeline, just like the boss still got a note saying Herman.

597
00:36:40,800 --> 00:36:47,200
But the specific information encoded in the nephew's original intention did not flow into the physical action.

598
00:36:47,960 --> 00:36:51,800
The physical outcome was generated purely by the random noise of his panic.

599
00:36:52,660 --> 00:36:54,940
It was a dark, cosmic coincidence.

600
00:36:55,500 --> 00:36:56,100
Precisely.

601
00:36:56,340 --> 00:37:00,760
And this is how information theory finally solves the problem of action.

602
00:37:00,760 --> 00:37:15,080
It proves mathematically that a true, voluntary action, a wink, and not just a blink, requires an unbroken, continuous flow of information from the cognitive source to the behavioral terminus.

603
00:37:15,160 --> 00:37:16,020
It's all about the flow.

604
00:37:16,600 --> 00:37:22,020
Causality in human behavior is not a billiard ball bouncing off another billiard ball.

605
00:37:22,020 --> 00:37:31,560
It is an ongoing, sustained signal that continuously constrains, corrects, and guides the physical body through space and time.

606
00:37:31,800 --> 00:37:39,840
If that signal is scrambled by noise or lost to equivocation, the resulting physical movement is divorced from your agency.

607
00:37:40,560 --> 00:37:43,440
It is an event, but it is not your action.

608
00:37:43,660 --> 00:37:49,820
So using information theory, we have completely torn down and rebuilt the mechanical model of how we act.

609
00:37:49,840 --> 00:37:50,520
We really have.

610
00:37:50,520 --> 00:37:54,680
But the implications of this shift don't stop at our physical movements.

611
00:37:55,100 --> 00:38:04,480
Because if our mechanical models of how we move our bodies are fundamentally broken, it turns out our mechanical models of how we process our feelings are equally disastrous.

612
00:38:05,420 --> 00:38:14,440
And this leads us directly into the second massive paradigm shift of this journey, moving from the physics of action into the complex world of human emotion.

613
00:38:14,440 --> 00:38:20,420
It is a perfect transition, because the exact same error occurred in both fields.

614
00:38:21,360 --> 00:38:34,580
Just as physicists and philosophers used to think of actions as billiard balls crashing into each other, psychologists and the general public have spent the last century thinking of emotions using a hydraulic model.

615
00:38:34,720 --> 00:38:37,200
Ah, the hydraulic model.

616
00:38:37,200 --> 00:38:44,000
Yeah, this is an incredibly pervasive idea that was heavily championed and popularized by Sigmund Freud.

617
00:38:44,160 --> 00:38:45,760
The whole pressure cooker model.

618
00:38:45,840 --> 00:38:46,420
Exactly.

619
00:38:47,080 --> 00:38:56,440
The hydraulic metaphor posits that human emotions, specifically intense negative emotions like anger, rage, or deep sadness function,

620
00:38:56,440 --> 00:39:02,440
like volatile fluids trapped under immense pressure inside a closed tank within your mind.

621
00:39:02,600 --> 00:39:03,920
Okay, I can picture that.

622
00:39:03,920 --> 00:39:12,380
The theory suggests that as you experience stress or frustration in your life, that internal tank slowly fills up with rage fluid.

623
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:15,180
The pressure builds against the walls of your psyche.

624
00:39:15,600 --> 00:39:20,980
And the core tenet of this model is that if you do not actively open a valve and let it all out,

625
00:39:21,280 --> 00:39:29,300
the pressure will continue to build until you suffer a catastrophic psychological explosion, resulting in a breakdown or sudden violence.

626
00:39:29,300 --> 00:39:34,220
And this mechanism of releasing the pressure is what we call catharsis.

627
00:39:34,340 --> 00:39:34,740
Yes.

628
00:39:35,020 --> 00:39:40,940
This idea is so deeply baked into our modern culture that we don't even question it anymore.

629
00:39:41,160 --> 00:39:43,160
You hear the vocabulary everywhere.

630
00:39:43,340 --> 00:39:46,200
A friend calls you and says, I just need to vent.

631
00:39:46,900 --> 00:39:49,580
We tell people who are grieving, just have a good cry.

632
00:39:49,720 --> 00:39:51,120
You need to get it out of your system.

633
00:39:51,180 --> 00:39:51,380
Right.

634
00:39:51,460 --> 00:39:52,140
It's everywhere.

635
00:39:52,140 --> 00:40:09,840
There is literally an entire booming industry of smash rooms where you pay $50 to put on safety goggles and destroy televisions and plates with a baseball bat specifically to, quote, release your anger.

636
00:40:10,160 --> 00:40:11,700
It's a huge business.

637
00:40:11,700 --> 00:40:18,580
And the reason it's so popular is because it feels so intuitively true to our physical experience.

638
00:40:19,240 --> 00:40:27,540
When I'm absolutely furious about something, my chest feels tight, my face is flushed, my heart is racing, I actually feel like a pressure cooker about to blow a gasket.

639
00:40:27,700 --> 00:40:29,580
The physical symptoms are very real.

640
00:40:29,720 --> 00:40:29,920
Right.

641
00:40:30,280 --> 00:40:39,940
And my immediate overwhelming instinct is to call a sympathetic friend and just unleash a 20-minute high-volume rant.

642
00:40:39,940 --> 00:40:42,840
I feel like I had to drain the tank to survive.

643
00:40:43,160 --> 00:40:49,720
The physical sensation is very real, but the mechanical metaphor we use to explain it is completely backward.

644
00:40:50,340 --> 00:40:53,660
And the empirical data is devastating to Freud's theory.

645
00:40:54,120 --> 00:40:54,860
Wait, really?

646
00:40:55,220 --> 00:40:55,680
Oh, yeah.

647
00:40:56,460 --> 00:41:06,800
Decades of rigorous psychological and physiological studies have repeatedly demonstrated that this hydraulic model of catharsis is scientifically incoherent.

648
00:41:06,800 --> 00:41:23,300
When researchers take subjects, deliberately induce a state of anger, and then provide them with an outlet to vent their frustration, like giving them a punching bag and telling them to think about the person who angered them, the subjects do not get less angry.

649
00:41:23,480 --> 00:41:24,920
Their tank does not drain.

650
00:41:25,100 --> 00:41:25,440
Wow.

651
00:41:25,700 --> 00:41:27,920
In fact, exactly the opposite happens.

652
00:41:27,920 --> 00:41:47,040
Hold on.

653
00:41:47,300 --> 00:41:50,040
Let me make sure I am fully understanding the magnitude of this.

654
00:41:50,040 --> 00:42:02,260
If I am furious at my boss, and I go to the gym and savagely beat a heavy bag for 20 minutes while screaming in my head, I am not actually draining any anger.

655
00:42:02,820 --> 00:42:08,720
Every therapist or self-help article that told me to get it out was giving me biologically harmful advice.

656
00:42:09,260 --> 00:42:11,200
Mathematically and biologically, yes.

657
00:42:11,600 --> 00:42:13,680
You are not opening a relief valve.

658
00:42:13,680 --> 00:42:21,640
The paper we are analyzing introduces a complex mathematical framework to explain exactly why venting fails.

659
00:42:22,120 --> 00:42:32,780
It proves that indulging the intense emotion through explosive catharsis actually amplifies the persistence of that emotion through resonant feedback loops.

660
00:42:32,960 --> 00:42:37,040
I read an analogy for this in the material that completely rewired my brain.

661
00:42:37,040 --> 00:42:40,500
Venting your anger isn't like draining a tank of water.

662
00:42:40,660 --> 00:42:46,080
It is like trying to stop a violent whirlpool by grabbing the paddle and vigorously stirring it.

663
00:42:46,180 --> 00:42:51,900
That is the most accurate visualization possible, and this is the moment we introduce the RSVP model.

664
00:42:51,960 --> 00:42:53,040
Okay, RSVP.

665
00:42:53,260 --> 00:42:57,080
It stands for the Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum.

666
00:42:57,080 --> 00:43:03,720
It is a dense acronym, but it represents a beautiful, elegant shift in how we view the brain.

667
00:43:03,720 --> 00:43:09,940
We have to permanently discard the image of the mind as a rigid metal tank holding fluid.

668
00:43:10,680 --> 00:43:16,540
Instead, we have to start visualizing the mind as a vast, continuous, topological landscape.

669
00:43:17,020 --> 00:43:22,600
A flowing, dynamic terrain defined by interacting fields of energy.

670
00:43:22,860 --> 00:43:24,480
Okay, let's explore this landscape.

671
00:43:24,720 --> 00:43:31,020
Let's unpack the RSVP model piece by piece, because once you see the mind this way, you can't unsee it.

672
00:43:31,020 --> 00:43:37,320
Walk me through the three foundational mathematical fields that construct this terrain of human consciousness.

673
00:43:38,260 --> 00:43:45,780
The RSVP model proposes that every cognitive state you experience is an emergent property of three distinct interacting fields.

674
00:43:46,400 --> 00:43:47,860
First, you have the scalar field.

675
00:43:48,380 --> 00:43:53,360
In layman's terms, think of this as your capacity, or your raw potential for action.

676
00:43:54,040 --> 00:43:59,100
It is the amount of metabolic and cognitive resource currently available in your brain.

677
00:43:59,100 --> 00:44:00,840
Okay, capacity, like a battery.

678
00:44:01,340 --> 00:44:02,840
Yeah, exactly like a battery.

679
00:44:03,160 --> 00:44:05,140
Second, you have the vector field.

680
00:44:05,820 --> 00:44:09,440
A vector requires direction, so think of this as flow.

681
00:44:09,560 --> 00:44:13,980
It represents the directional momentum of your attention, your thoughts, and your behavior.

682
00:44:14,720 --> 00:44:18,380
Where is your mental energy pointing, and how fast is it moving there?

683
00:44:18,440 --> 00:44:19,360
Flow, got it.

684
00:44:19,540 --> 00:44:21,620
And third, you have the entropy field.

685
00:44:22,400 --> 00:44:28,860
Entropy is a measure of disorder, so in this landscape, it represents chaos or local uncertainty.

686
00:44:29,780 --> 00:44:33,520
How unpredictable is the environment you are currently navigating?

687
00:44:34,020 --> 00:44:37,440
So we have a landscape built out of capacity, flow, and chaos.

688
00:44:38,180 --> 00:44:45,780
How do those abstract physics terms translate into the very real feeling of being sad or angry or joyful?

689
00:44:46,560 --> 00:44:50,180
Where do the actual emotions live in this terrain?

690
00:44:50,180 --> 00:44:54,280
In the RSVP model, an emotion is not an object you possess.

691
00:44:54,860 --> 00:44:55,860
It is not a noun.

692
00:44:56,180 --> 00:44:58,000
An emotion is an attractor basin.

693
00:44:58,200 --> 00:44:59,480
An attractor basin?

694
00:44:59,480 --> 00:44:59,840
Yes.

695
00:45:00,080 --> 00:45:04,960
It is a literal valley or depression that forms in the topological landscape of your mind.

696
00:45:05,540 --> 00:45:10,580
When this specific combination of capacity, flow, and chaos interacts, the terrain warps.

697
00:45:11,100 --> 00:45:16,240
And when your attention and cognitive energy get pulled down into one of these deep valleys by gravity,

698
00:45:16,240 --> 00:45:18,940
you subjectively experience an emotion.

699
00:45:19,220 --> 00:45:20,660
That makes so much sense.

700
00:45:20,660 --> 00:45:29,800
The researchers translate those three mathematical fields into three highly familiar psychological dimensions to help us map the valleys.

701
00:45:30,120 --> 00:45:33,580
They are arousal, valence, and dominance.

702
00:45:34,060 --> 00:45:36,600
Okay, I know these terms from basic psychology.

703
00:45:36,860 --> 00:45:39,620
Let's map them onto our new mental terrain.

704
00:45:39,880 --> 00:45:41,660
Let's start with arousal.

705
00:45:41,660 --> 00:45:48,020
In this model, arousal represents how turbulent and energetic the landscape is.

706
00:45:48,200 --> 00:45:52,240
It is the sheer volume of kinetic energy coursing through the system.

707
00:45:53,020 --> 00:45:58,880
A state of low arousal would look like a flat, calm, gently rolling plane.

708
00:45:59,740 --> 00:46:07,140
High arousal means the terrain is violent, incredibly steep slopes, jagged cliffs, and fast-moving currents of energy.

709
00:46:07,300 --> 00:46:08,080
And valence.

710
00:46:08,080 --> 00:46:13,480
Valence represents the direction of the flow relative to your personal internal goals.

711
00:46:14,040 --> 00:46:18,200
Are you being pushed toward something beneficial or dragged toward something harmful?

712
00:46:18,840 --> 00:46:22,640
Positive valence means the flow of the landscape aligns with what you want.

713
00:46:23,080 --> 00:46:28,720
Negative valence means the current is actively pushing you away from your goals or toward a threat.

714
00:46:28,820 --> 00:46:29,880
And what about dominance?

715
00:46:30,120 --> 00:46:32,360
That one always feels a bit abstract to me.

716
00:46:32,360 --> 00:46:39,740
Dominance tracks the state of the system as a whole, specifically, whether your sphere of influence is expanding or contracting.

717
00:46:40,420 --> 00:46:46,920
Do you feel like you are in control, expanding your presence, and successfully navigating the terrain?

718
00:46:47,420 --> 00:46:52,880
Or do you feel trapped, overwhelmed, and shrinking away from an insurmountable obstacle?

719
00:46:52,880 --> 00:46:57,420
So, let's take these tools and go back to the anger whirlpool.

720
00:46:57,840 --> 00:47:02,100
Let's say someone rear-ends my car and they jump out and start yelling at me.

721
00:47:02,500 --> 00:47:04,580
I am instantly furious.

722
00:47:05,040 --> 00:47:12,520
In the RSVP model, I have just been dragged into a very deep, very steep valley of negative valence.

723
00:47:12,520 --> 00:47:14,380
The situation is bad.

724
00:47:15,040 --> 00:47:16,940
The arousal is extremely high.

725
00:47:17,040 --> 00:47:18,140
My heart is pounding.

726
00:47:18,620 --> 00:47:20,440
The terrain is churning with energy.

727
00:47:21,120 --> 00:47:23,840
The old catharsis model tacks me on the shoulder and says,

728
00:47:23,960 --> 00:47:26,920
yell back at them, hit your steering wheel, release the pressure.

729
00:47:27,260 --> 00:47:30,420
When I actually do that, when I start screaming and venting,

730
00:47:30,720 --> 00:47:33,800
what is physically and mathematically happening to that valley?

731
00:47:33,980 --> 00:47:40,140
You are injecting massive amounts of kinetic energy directly into an already unstable system.

732
00:47:40,140 --> 00:47:43,100
In the language of dynamical systems and physics,

733
00:47:43,260 --> 00:47:46,420
you are inducing what is called a Hoff bifurcation.

734
00:47:46,740 --> 00:47:48,220
A Hoff bifurcation.

735
00:47:48,740 --> 00:47:52,400
Let's break that down, because it sounds like something that happens to a dying star,

736
00:47:52,560 --> 00:47:54,020
not a guy in a traffic jam.

737
00:47:54,340 --> 00:47:56,340
It's a profound concept, really.

738
00:47:56,960 --> 00:48:00,740
Imagine a simple pendulum swinging gently back and forth.

739
00:48:00,860 --> 00:48:02,120
It's a stable system.

740
00:48:02,920 --> 00:48:07,460
Now, imagine you start feeding extra energy into that pendulum

741
00:48:07,460 --> 00:48:10,940
by pushing it harder and harder at random intervals.

742
00:48:11,940 --> 00:48:14,720
Eventually, the system can't handle the extra energy.

743
00:48:15,120 --> 00:48:19,380
It undergoes a bifurcation, a sudden radical change in its behavior.

744
00:48:19,860 --> 00:48:24,880
The pendulum stops swinging smoothly and starts oscillating wildly,

745
00:48:25,160 --> 00:48:27,840
chaotically, just spinning out of control.

746
00:48:28,160 --> 00:48:29,080
So I'm the pendulum.

747
00:48:29,380 --> 00:48:29,680
Yes.

748
00:48:29,680 --> 00:48:34,040
When you are trapped in an anger valley, your mind is that pendulum.

749
00:48:35,020 --> 00:48:38,620
By choosing to vent, scream, or hit a punching bag,

750
00:48:38,840 --> 00:48:40,180
you aren't draining a tank.

751
00:48:40,340 --> 00:48:43,660
You are feeding violent kinetic energy into the attractor basin.

752
00:48:44,200 --> 00:48:48,360
The mathematics of the RSVP model prove that this influx of energy

753
00:48:48,360 --> 00:48:53,240
makes the walls of the emotional valley much steeper and the currents much faster.

754
00:48:53,640 --> 00:48:53,840
Wow.

755
00:48:54,040 --> 00:48:56,880
You are creating a resonant feedback loop.

756
00:48:56,880 --> 00:48:59,440
You are literally digging the hole deeper,

757
00:48:59,660 --> 00:49:04,760
trapping yourself in that aggressive state for a significantly longer period of time.

758
00:49:05,220 --> 00:49:06,960
This is genuinely terrifying.

759
00:49:07,880 --> 00:49:10,120
Because the release I feel when I yell.

760
00:49:10,280 --> 00:49:10,500
Yeah.

761
00:49:10,980 --> 00:49:13,180
It feels so good for about three seconds.

762
00:49:13,380 --> 00:49:17,160
Are you saying that feeling of relief is just a biological lie?

763
00:49:17,460 --> 00:49:21,120
It is a severe misinterpretation of your own data.

764
00:49:21,560 --> 00:49:23,960
What feels like a release when you scream at someone

765
00:49:23,960 --> 00:49:28,360
is usually just a very transient, fleeting shift in the dominance field.

766
00:49:28,820 --> 00:49:31,100
For one split second, by yelling louder,

767
00:49:31,480 --> 00:49:34,760
